\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The work order is the non-negotiable unit of accountability for all work performed by the Information Operations Department.
 This policy establishes the work order as the authoritative record of why a task was undertaken,
 who authorized it,
 what was done,
 and how it was resolved.
 Work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement govern the technical anatomy of work orders —
 field definitions,
 status workflows,
 category taxonomy,
 and the terminal closure state —
 and are incorporated by reference throughout this policy.
 Where this policy establishes procedural mandates,
 work order operational standards provide the operational detail for executing them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Work Order as Universal Requirement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall create a work order for every actionable task,
 without exception.
 This obligation applies regardless of whether the work is reactive or proactive,
 regardless of the channel through which the work was identified or requested,
 and regardless of the estimated duration or complexity of the task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
No Information Operations Personnel shall perform IT work,
 or make a commitment to perform IT work,
 without an associated work order.
 The absence of a work order for completed work constitutes a documentation failure regardless of the operational outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The creation of a work order indicates that a request has been submitted to the Information Operations Department for evaluation.
 It does not guarantee acceptance or execution.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall disposition work orders that fall outside the scope of Information Operations responsibilities,
 that are submitted for Unsupported assets,
 or that cannot be resourced within current operational capacity in accordance with work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement and this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Intake and Channel Routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The designated work order system is the authoritative intake channel for all service requests.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall route requests received through any other channel to the work order system immediately,
 and in all cases no later than one (1) business hour following the receipt of the request or the initiation of the task,
 whichever occurs first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Walk-in requests
\series default
:
 When a County employee presents a request in person,
 the receiving Information Operations Personnel shall direct the requester to submit the request through the work order system.
 Where the requester is unable to do so,
 the receiving Information Operations Personnel shall create the work order on the requester's behalf,
 ensuring that the Requested By field accurately identifies the actual requester in accordance with work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Telephone requests
\series default
:
 The receiving Information Operations Personnel shall handle requests received by telephone in the same manner as walk-in requests.
 The receiving Information Operations Personnel shall create a work order concurrent with or immediately following the call and shall document the substance of the conversation in the work order notes in accordance with the out-of-band summarization requirements of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Communications Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Email and informal digital communications
\series default
:
 The receiving Information Operations Personnel shall route requests received by email or other informal digital channels to the work order system.
 The receiving Information Operations Personnel shall summarize the communication in the work order notes in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
In all cases,
 the work order is the record of the request.
 Channel acknowledgment to the requester —
 including verbal or informal confirmation —
 does not substitute for work order creation.
 Information Operations Personnel shall not begin work on a request prior to work order creation except as provided under the emergency exception in Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 IT-Initiated Work Orders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department regularly initiates work that is not triggered by a user request.
 This includes infrastructure maintenance,
 proactive upgrades,
 compliance remediations,
 internal projects,
 and any other IT-driven activity that constitutes actionable work.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall create a work order for all IT-initiated work,
 and all IT-initiated work orders shall be designated using the Internal Project checkbox as defined in the System of Engagement.
 The Internal Project designation is mandatory for all IT-initiated work without exception.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Authorization requirements for IT-initiated work orders are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Routine IT-initiated tasks
\series default
:
 The assigned technician may authorize routine IT-initiated tasks —
 including scheduled maintenance,
 standard configuration updates,
 and minor proactive remediations —
 in accordance with their defined role authority under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Delegation of Authority and Decision Rights).
 The assigned technician shall document the basis for authorization in the work order at the time of creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Non-routine or significant IT-initiated tasks
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director or IT Director shall authorize non-routine or significant IT-initiated tasks —
 including infrastructure changes,
 new deployments,
 system decommissions,
 or any task that materially alters the County's operational technology environment —
 prior to work commencement.
 The authorizing official's name and the basis for authorization shall be documented in the work order before work begins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Project-level IT-initiated work
\series default
:
 IT-initiated work that meets project-level thresholds —
 as determined by scope,
 resource requirements,
 or duration —
 shall additionally be subject to the project management requirements of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.14"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (IT Project Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Triage and Authorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall triage all work orders prior to the commencement of active work,
 in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Triage confirms or reclassifies the severity level,
 validates scope,
 identifies the applicable asset support classification,
 and initiates or queues the appropriate response.
 Information Operations Personnel shall not begin work on a work order until triage is complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Where a submitted work order lacks sufficient information to complete triage,
 the assigned technician or queue reviewer shall document the triage attempt,
 specify the information required,
 and notify the requester that more information is needed.
 The work order shall remain in Queued status for the duration of this pending information period.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall pause service level clocks for the duration of the pending information period and shall resume them upon receipt of the required information from the requester.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall close work orders that remain without requester response for five (5) consecutive business days,
 with closure rationale documented in the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Waiting for User status,
 as defined in the System of Engagement,
 applies during the active execution phase of a work order when an IT-side action cannot proceed due to a user-side dependency —
 not during triage.
 The assigned technician shall apply Waiting for User status in accordance with work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement when that condition is encountered after triage and work commencement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall close work orders triaged for Unsupported assets immediately with a documented replacement referral,
 in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 No remediation shall be performed on Unsupported assets.
 The assigned technician or queue reviewer shall confirm the lifecycle status of Deprecated assets during triage and shall initiate the labor ceiling monitoring obligations defined in Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Deprecated Asset Labor Ceiling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department operates on the principle that unreliable tools are replaced rather than indefinitely maintained.
 For Deprecated assets —
 those already formally identified for replacement —
 this principle governs remediation decisions.
 The Department's obligation is to keep the user functional for the duration of the replacement window,
 not to restore a failing asset to full health.
 Where an asset demonstrates a pattern of failure that undermines that reliability,
 the appropriate response is to accelerate replacement,
 not to continue investing remediation labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This framework operates through one (1) objective trigger and a Technician Judgment Pathway.
 Either activates the disposition review process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Objective Trigger —
 Incident Frequency
\series default
:
 A Deprecated asset shall be flagged for disposition review when it generates five (5) or more reactive work orders within the same category within any rolling ninety (90) calendar day window.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The same-category requirement is essential.
 Five or more reactive tickets across different categories may indicate a heavily utilized asset.
 Five or more within the same category indicates a specific,
 repeating failure pattern in that functional dimension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Tickets in different categories do not aggregate toward this trigger,
 even if the total exceeds five (5).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
For purposes of this trigger,
 reactive work orders are those submitted in response to asset failures or degradation,
 as distinct from IT-initiated maintenance or proactive work orders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monitoring Accountability
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a monitoring mechanism —
 whether automated reporting,
 periodic query,
 or scheduled review —
 sufficient to identify Deprecated assets approaching or crossing the objective trigger threshold.
 The monitoring method shall be documented in work order operational standards maintained in the System of Engagement.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Technician Judgment Pathway
\series default
:
 The assigned technician may initiate a disposition review for any Deprecated asset at any time,
 independent of whether the objective trigger has been crossed.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall enter a written technical assessment in the work order record identifying the specific observations,
 failure patterns,
 or reliability concerns supporting the recommendation.
 Qualitative characterizations without supporting observations do not satisfy this requirement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Rationale
\series default
:
 This pathway is the primary mechanism of this framework.
 Reliability failure does not always express itself in countable tickets —
 it expresses itself in whether the asset can be depended upon.
 That judgment,
 when documented,
 is sufficient basis for a disposition review.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Disposition Review Process
\series default
:
 When a Deprecated asset is flagged under either mechanism,
 the following review process shall apply.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Notification
\series default
:
 The technician or queue reviewer who identifies the trigger condition shall notify the Assistant IT Director within one (1) business day,
 with a summary of the trigger conditions or technician assessment and the relevant work order history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Assistant IT Director Review
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review the flagged asset within three (3) business days of notification and shall determine whether the existing replacement timeline remains appropriate or whether escalation to the IT Director is warranted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Disposition Authority
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director may authorize the following disposition without IT Director escalation:
 confirm that the existing replacement timeline remains appropriate and direct that remediation continue within existing parameters.
 The following dispositions require IT Director approval:
 (a) authorize replacement acceleration;
 or (b) authorize continued remediation beyond the standard labor ceiling in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IT Director Escalation
\series default
:
 Where the Assistant IT Director determines that replacement acceleration or continued remediation beyond the standard labor ceiling is warranted,
 the Assistant IT Director shall escalate to the IT Director with a written recommendation within one (1) business day of completing the review.
 The IT Director shall issue a written disposition decision within five (5) business days of escalation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Documentation
\series default
:
 The official who renders the disposition decision shall document the decision in the relevant work order and in the IT Asset Catalog entry for the asset.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Proximity-to-Deadline Standard
\series default
:
 The assigned technician shall apply a restricted remediation standard to Deprecated assets with an established replacement deadline within thirty (30) calendar days of the date of triage.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall limit remediation to maintaining basic operational capability sufficient for the user to perform their assigned job function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Full objective trigger framework analysis is not required for assets already imminently scheduled for replacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Clarification
\series default
:
 This exemption applies to the objective trigger analysis only.
 The Technician Judgment Pathway remains available at all times regardless of replacement timeline proximity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall inform the user of the replacement timeline and advise of any available interim workarounds.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exclusions from Disposition Decisions
\series default
:
 The following factors are explicitly excluded from consideration in any disposition decision made under this framework.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Sunk cost
\series default
:
 Prior investment in consumables,
 supplies,
 parts,
 or remediation labor is not a factor.
 The IT Director or Assistant IT Director shall evaluate disposition on the basis of forward-looking operational analysis only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
End-user workflow disruption and preference
\series default
:
 If the user can perform their assigned job function,
 the operational standard is met.
 User preferences regarding specific equipment shall not influence disposition decisions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
